messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

I found three routes defined in app/api/cms/log.py. They are registered under the cms blueprint (url_prefix="/cms") and then under the log blueprint (url_prefix="/log"), so the full paths are:

1) Path: /cms/log
- All methods: False
- HEAD: False
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: False
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

2) Path: /cms/log/search
- All methods: False
- HEAD: False
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: False
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

3) Path: /cms/log/users
- All methods: False
- HEAD: False
- POST: False
- OPTIONS: False
- TRACE: False
- GET: True
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

Explanation
- In app/__init__.py the CMS blueprint is registered with url_prefix="/cms": app.register_blueprint(create_cms(), url_prefix="/cms").
- In app/api/cms/__init__.py the log blueprint (log_api) is registered with url_prefix="/log": cms.register_blueprint(log_api, url_prefix="/log").
- The routes in app/api/cms/log.py are declared with @log_api.route("") (empty), @log_api.route("/search"), and @log_api.route("/users"), so after the two prefixes the full paths are /cms/log, /cms/log/search and /cms/log/users.
- Each view function uses @log_api.route(...) without an explicit methods=... argument. That indicates the route defined in the source maps to the GET handler in the code; therefore GET is marked as acceptable.
- The code does not explicitly declare HEAD, OPTIONS, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, TRACE, or "all methods" anywhere for these routes, so those methods are marked as not acceptable based on the code (per the instruction to base acceptance on code content rather than framework runtime behavior).
